Lab 4 Generalization exercises

Problem #1

# get 1000 samples with 10 scores each

scores <- rnorm(1000*10,100,25)
samples <- rep(1:1000,each=10)
my_df <- data.frame(samples,scores)

# get the means of the samples

sample_means <- my_df %>%
                group_by(samples) %>%
                summarise(means=mean(scores))

# make a histogram

 ggplot(sample_means, aes(x=means))+
  geom_histogram(color="white")+
  theme_classic()

# part a

 ggplot(sample_means, aes(x=means))+
  geom_histogram(color="white")+
  theme_classic()

# part b
mean(sample_means$means)
## [1] 100.1798
# part c

sd(sample_means$means)
## [1] 7.8546

                group_by(samples) %>%
                summarise(means=mean(scores))

# make a histogram

  geom_histogram(color="white")+
  theme_classic()

Lab 4 Written answer question

  1. Sampling error occurs when the sample chosen for statistical analysis fails to accurately represent the population as a whole, resulting in faulty statistical conclusions. Sampling error is an omnipresent problem in psychological research because taking population measurments is often unrealistic. A random sampling method can reduce certain forms of systematic errors.

  2. As sample size increases, the standard deviation of the sampling distribution of the mean gets smaller because a larger sample size is more representative of the population rather than a small sample size, which is more subject to randomness.
